Module: vioblk.sys -- virtio-blk SCSI miniport.  Lifted-and-adapted
from Red Hat's KVM Windows guest drivers (viostor); the SCSI
translation logic comes from there.  PCI/transport/queue management
go through MicroNT's shared virtio.lib (NTOS/VIRTIO/), the same
library backing vionet/viorng/vioser/vioinput.

Builds as a SCSI miniport on top of NT 3.5's scsiport.sys; SCSIDISK
presents the SRB stream as \Device\Harddisk<N>\Partition<P> to the
rest of the OS, exactly the way nvme2k.sys does for NVMe.

Modern transport only (PCI capabilities + MMIO), single queue, INTx
interrupts -- no MSI-X, no multi-queue, no DISCARD/WRITE_ZEROES,
no crash-dump support.  Read/write/flush is the boot-disk surface.

Upstream reference:
    https://github.com/virtio-win/kvm-guest-drivers-windows/tree/master/viostor

PCI device IDs:
    0x1AF4 / 0x1042  (modern virtio-blk)
    0x1AF4 / 0x1001  (transitional virtio-blk -- QEMU's default for
                      `-device virtio-blk-pci`)

QEMU exposes this with `-device virtio-blk-pci,drive=...`.

!ENDIF

MAJORCOMP=ntos
MINORCOMP=dd

TARGETNAME=vioblk
TARGETPATH=$(BASEDIR)\public\sdk\lib
TARGETTYPE=MINIPORT

INCLUDES=..\..\inc;..\..\virtio\inc

# scsiport for the SCSI miniport API; virtio for our PCI/queue
# transport.  Plus ntoskrnl + hal for the Mm/Hal/READ_REGISTER calls
# our virtio.lib makes directly -- MAKEFILE.DEF's MINIPORT TARGETTYPE
# doesn't auto-include them (DRIVER does, but MINIPORT assumes
# scsiport wraps everything; our virtio.lib bypasses that).
TARGETLIBS=$(BASEDIR)\public\sdk\lib\*\scsiport.lib \
           $(BASEDIR)\public\sdk\lib\*\virtio.lib  \
           $(BASEDIR)\public\sdk\lib\*\ntoskrnl.lib \
           $(BASEDIR)\public\sdk\lib\*\hal.lib

SOURCES=vioblk.c    \
        scsi.c      \
        vioblk.rc
